ed, and the unfolding of Soviet and international events in the months after his death. Rubenstein throws fresh light onthe devious plotting of Beria, Malenkov, Khrushchev, and other “comrades in arms” who well understood the significance of the dictator’s impending death;the witness-documented events of his death as compared to official published versions;Stalin’s rumored plans to forcibly exile Soviet Jews;the responses of Eisenhower and Secretary of State Dulles to the Kremlin’s conciliatory gestures after Stalin’s death; andthe momentous repercussions when Stalin’s regime of terror was cut short.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHeads of statezSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aSocial changezSoviet UnionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106677140 cprintz978030019222340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021676940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300216769423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300216769/original  a978-3-11-066771-4  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY